<section class="card">
  <h2>About Swiss Chard</h2>

  <p class="tagline">
    Cool-season workhorse—tolerates light frost and steady through temperature swings.
  </p>

  <p class="lede">
    <strong>Swiss chard tolerates light frost and spans a wide temperature range.</strong>
    For GrowByDate modeling, frost is defined as 32°F (0°C). In a typical year (1991–2020 climate normals at the 50% probability level), Swiss chard is rarely limited by first frost. Instead, viability depends on steady growth and sufficient seasonal heat for leaf production before sustained hard freeze.
  </p>

  <p>
    In short seasons, chard is valuable because it bridges cool spring conditions and early fall cooling. It offers more heat tolerance than spinach and more frost tolerance than many warm-season crops.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Quick Planning Reference</h2>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Start indoors (optional):</strong> 4–6 weeks before transplant window</li>
    <li><strong>Direct sow:</strong> 2 weeks before to 2 weeks after last frost</li>
    <li><strong>Days to maturity:</strong> 50–70 days (variety-dependent)</li>
    <li><strong>Frost tolerance:</strong> Light to moderate (handles light frost; hard freezes damage leaves)</li>
  </ul>

  <p class="fine muted">
    These are baseline planning ranges. Chard is adaptable but still constrained by sustained freeze.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Temperature Profile</h2>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Optimal growth:</strong> 55–75°F (13–24°C)</li>
    <li><strong>Slow growth:</strong> Below ~40°F (4°C)</li>
    <li><strong>Heat tolerance:</strong> Better than spinach; tolerates moderate summer warmth</li>
    <li><strong>Planning frost boundary:</strong> 32°F (0°C)</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    Swiss chard tolerates light frost near 32°F (0°C), but repeated or hard freezes can damage leaves and halt production.
    In many climates, chard continues harvest into fall until sustained freezing occurs.
  </p>

  <p class="fine">
    For frost intensity definitions, see:
    <a href="/guides/light-freeze-vs-hard-freeze/">Light freeze vs hard freeze</a>.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Spring & Fall Timing</h2>

  <p>
    Chard performs well in both early spring and fall plantings:
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Spring crop:</strong> Sow or transplant early for steady growth into summer.</li>
    <li><strong>Fall crop:</strong> Count backward from first frost and allow buffer for slower late-season growth.</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    Use the <a href="/tools/first-frost-planner/">First Frost Planner</a> to anchor fall sowing dates.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Typical GDD Requirement</h2>

  <p><strong>Base temperature:</strong> 50°F (10°C)</p>
  <p><strong>Approximate GDD needed:</strong> ~600–1,000 GDD (base 50) for steady leaf production</p>

  <p>
    Swiss chard has a moderate heat requirement. In cool summers, maturity may extend slightly beyond label timing, but overall GDD demand remains manageable in most short-season climates.
  </p>

  <p class="fine muted" style="margin-top:14px;">
    GDD = ((Daily High + Daily Low) ÷ 2) − 50
  </p>

  <div class="actions">
    <a class="button subtle" href="/tools/growing-degree-day-planner/">Use the GDD Planner</a>
  </div>

  <p class="fine">
    For how frost windows and seasonal heat work together, see:
    <a href="/guides/how-frost-dates-and-growing-degree-days-work-together/">How frost dates and Growing Degree Days work together</a>.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Minimum Frost-Free Days</h2>

  <p>
    Most Swiss chard varieties begin harvest in <strong>50–70 frost-free days</strong>.
    Because chard tolerates light frost, effective harvest windows may extend slightly beyond first frost in mild conditions.
  </p>

  <div class="actions">
    <a class="button subtle" href="/tools/frost-date-finder/">Check Your Frost-Free Season</a>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Short-Season Viability Flag</h2>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Good choice under 100 days?</strong> Yes (reliable and adaptable)</li>
    <li><strong>Risky under 90 days?</strong> Rarely; moderate heat requirement and frost tolerance provide margin</li>
    <li><strong>Needs season extension?</strong> Occasionally helpful in late fall (light cover for freeze protection)</li>
  </ul>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>First Frost Sensitivity</h2>

  <p>
    Swiss chard tolerates light frost near 32°F (0°C), but sustained hard freezes will damage leaves and halt growth.
    For modeling consistency, treat 32°F (0°C) as the frost boundary while recognizing chard’s moderate tolerance.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Early-Maturing Strategy</h2>

  <ul>
    <li>Sow early in spring to maximize runway</li>
    <li>Select early varieties in tight frost windows</li>
    <li>Use full sun exposure to preserve effective heat accumulation</li>
    <li>For fall crops, allow additional buffer for slower late-season growth</li>
  </ul>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Planning Model</h2>

  <p class="muted">
    Frost → Season Length → GDD → Crop Requirement → Risk Margin
  </p>

  <p>
    In a typical year, Swiss chard is viable in most short-season climates because its moderate heat requirement and frost tolerance provide natural buffer.
    The primary limitation is sustained hard freeze, not first frost itself.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

  <h3>Can Swiss chard survive frost?</h3>
  <p>
    Yes. Swiss chard tolerates light frost near 32°F (0°C), though repeated hard freezes eventually halt growth.
  </p>

  <h3>Is chard better than spinach in summer?</h3>
  <p>
    Often yes. Swiss chard tolerates warmer temperatures better than spinach before bolting.
  </p>

  <h3>Is Swiss chard reliable in short seasons?</h3>
  <p>
    Yes. Its moderate GDD requirement and frost tolerance make it adaptable in tight frost windows.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Summary</h2>

  <ul>
    <li>Use 32°F (0°C) as the frost boundary (50% probability, 1991–2020 normals).</li>
    <li>Swiss chard tolerates light frost and moderate heat.</li>
    <li>Typical requirement: 50–70 days, ~600–1,000 GDD (base 50).</li>
    <li>Model viability using frost window + seasonal heat budget + variety requirement + risk margin.</li>
  </ul>
</section>